'''Ricardo Daniel Pepi''' (born January 9, 2003) is an American professional [[Association football|soccer]] player who plays as a [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]] for {{Dutch football updater|PSVEindho}} club [[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]] and the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States national team]].

Pepi had his breakthrough with [[Major League Soccer]] club [[FC Dallas]] and was named the [[MLS Young Player of the Year Award|MLS Young Player of the Year]] in [[2021 Major League Soccer season|2021]]. In 2022 he joined [[Bundesliga]] club [[FC Augsburg]] and was later loaned to Eredivisie club [[FC Groningen]]. In 2023 he signed with [[PSV Eindhoven]] for €9 million ($9.8m) and won the [[2023–24 Eredivisie]].<ref name=":1">{{Cite web |date=2023-07-07 |title=PSV announce signing USMNT striker Pepi |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/37972983/psv-confirm-signing-usmnt-striker-ricardo-pepi-augsburg |access-date=2023-09-13 |website=ESPN.com |language=en}}</ref>

He represented the United States at the youth U17 level. He made his senior debut in 2021 and won the [[CONCACAF Nations League]] in [[2023 CONCACAF Nations League Finals|2023]] and [[2024 CONCACAF Nations League Finals|2024]].<ref name=":0" /> He won the [[U.S. Soccer Young Male Player of the Year]] award in 2021.

==Early life==
Pepi was born in [[El Paso, Texas]], and raised in nearby [[San Elizario, Texas|San Elizario]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bloomquist |first1=Bret |title=FC Dallas signs 16-year-old El Pasoan Ricardo Pepi |url=https://www.elpasotimes.com/story/sports/soccer/2019/06/21/fc-dallas-el-paso-16-year-old-ricardo-pepi/1529936001/ |access-date=September 8, 2021 |work=El Paso Times |date=June 21, 2019}}</ref> He is of [[Mexicans|Mexican]] descent, and he regularly travels to [[Ciudad Juárez]] to visit family.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Becherano |first1=Lizzy |title=Ricardo Pepi pledges international allegiance to USMNT over Mexico |url=https://www.90min.com/posts/ricardo-pepi-international-allegiance-usmnt-mexico |access-date=September 9, 2021 |work=90min |date=August 27, 2021}}</ref> Pepi began playing recreational soccer when he was only four years old in local El Paso leagues.<ref name="dmn1">{{cite news |last1=Arnold |first1=John |title=How Ricardo Pepi went from FC Dallas teenage sensation to MLS All-Star |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/sports/fc-dallas/2021/08/25/how-ricardo-pepi-went-from-fc-dallas-teenage-sensation-to-mls-all-star/ |access-date=September 8, 2021 |work=The Dallas Morning News |date=August 25, 2021}}</ref> He soon began playing competitive organized soccer for a club coached by his father, Daniel Pepi.<ref name="dmn1"/> The club would soon become affiliated with [[Major League Soccer]] club [[FC Dallas]], who scouted Pepi following the Copa Chivas tournament in 2016, offering the then 13-year old the opportunity to join the FC Dallas youth academy.<ref name="dmn1"/>

In his first season, Pepi was put into the under-13 side and scored 18 goals in just 15 games, leading him to rise up the ranks within the club.<ref name="dn1">{{cite news |title=FC Dallas signs Ricardo Pepi to USL team |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/sports/fc-dallas/2018/12/07/fc-dallas-signs-ricardo-pepi-to-usl-team/ |access-date=September 9, 2021 |work=Dallas Morning News |date=December 6, 2018}}</ref> He was soon promoted to the under-17 side as a 15-year old, scoring 19 goals in eight matches.<ref name="dn1"/>

==Club career==

===North Texas SC===
On December 8, 2018, Pepi became the first signing for [[North Texas SC]], the new affiliate club for [[FC Dallas]] in [[USL League One]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Carrick |first1=Buzz |title=FC Dallas signs Ricardo Pepi to USL team |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/sports/fc-dallas/2018/12/07/fc-dallas-signs-ricardo-pepi-to-usl-team/ |access-date=September 8, 2021 |work=Dallas Morning News |date=December 6, 2018}}</ref> On March 30, 2019, he made his professional debut in North Texas SC's first ever match, scoring a hat-trick in a 3–2 victory over the [[Chattanooga Red Wolves SC|Chattanooga Red Wolves]].<ref>{{cite web |title=North Texas SC 3-2 Chattanooga Red Wolves |url=https://us.soccerway.com/matches/2019/03/31/united-states/usl-league-one/north-texas/chattanooga-red-wolves/2945938/ |website=Soccerway}}</ref> Following the match, North Texas SC head coach [[Eric Quill]] stated: "I'd like to say that it shocks me, but it doesn't shock me. He's been in unbelievable form in the preseason. Every game, he's growing. He's got such a hunger to score goals, that is rare. He can finish in any way."<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kafai |first1=Arman |title=North Texas SC wins first match in history, defeat Chattanooga Red Wolves 3-2 |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/sports/fc-dallas/2019/03/31/north-texas-sc-wins-first-match-in-history-defeat-chatanooga-red-wolves-3-2/ |access-date=September 8, 2021 |work=Dallas Morning News |date=March 30, 2019}}</ref>

In the following match against [[Forward Madison FC|Forward Madison]], Pepi scored for the second match in a row deep into second half stoppage time to give North Texas SC the 1–0 home victory.<ref>{{cite web |title=North Texas SC 1–0 Forward Madison |url=https://us.soccerway.com/matches/2019/04/14/united-states/usl-league-one/north-texas/forward-madison/2946789/ |website=Soccerway}}</ref> He was then called into the international [[United States men's national under-17 soccer team|under-17]] squad. When he returned, Pepi scored again in his third game of the season against [[Lansing Ignite FC|Lansing Ignite]] in a 2–2 draw.<ref>{{cite web |title=Lansing Ignite 2–2 North Texas SC |url=https://us.soccerway.com/matches/2019/05/19/united-states/usl-league-one/lansing-ignite/north-texas/2946811/ |website=Soccerway}}</ref>

On October 12, 2019, Pepi returned to North Texas SC for the semifinals of the [[2019 USL League One season#Semifinals|USL League One playoffs]]. He scored a brace for North Texas SC against [[Forward Madison FC|Forward Madison]] in a 2–0 home victory, advancing the side to the final.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Carrick |first1=Buzz |title=North Texas Soccer Club advances to the USL League One Final with 2-0 win over Forward Madison |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/sports/fc-dallas/2019/10/13/north-texas-soccer-club-advances-to-the-usl-league-one-final-with-2-0-win-over-forward-madison/ |access-date=September 9, 2021 |work=Dallas Morning News |date=October 13, 2019}}</ref> After the match, Pepi was called into the under-17 side, thus not being available for selection against [[Greenville Triumph SC|Greenville Triumph]] in the final on October 19.<ref name="final1">{{cite news |last1=Lenard |first1=John |title=North Texas Soccer Club triumphs over Greenville, wins inaugural USL-1 Final |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/sports/fc-dallas/2019/10/20/north-texas-soccer-club-triumphs-over-greenville-wins-inaugural-usl-1-final/ |access-date=September 9, 2021 |work=Dallas Morning News |date=October 19, 2019}}</ref> Despite his absence, North Texas SC proceeded to win the match 1–0 through [[Arturo Rodríguez (footballer, born 1998)|Arturo Rodríguez]], thus winning their first championship and giving Pepi his first trophy.<ref name="final1"/> Pepi was named as a finalist for the USL Young Player of the Year on October 17, but lost out to Arturo Rodríguez.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Carrick |first1=Buzz |title=Arturo Rodriguez named USL League One Young Player of the Year |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/sports/fc-dallas/2019/10/31/arturo-rodriguez-named-usl-league-one-young-player-of-the-year/ |access-date=September 9, 2021 |work=Dallas Morning News |date=October 31, 2019}}</ref>

===FC Dallas===
On June 11, 2019, Pepi was loaned to [[North Texas SC]] parent club [[FC Dallas]] on a short-term loan ahead of their [[U.S. Open Cup]] match against [[OKC Energy FC|OKC Energy]].<ref>{{cite news |title=FC Dallas Acquires Forward Ricardo Pepi On Loan from North Texas SC |url=https://www.fcdallas.com/news/fc-dallas-acquires-forward-ricardo-pepi-loan-north-texas-sc |access-date=September 8, 2021 |work=FC Dallas |date=June 11, 2019}}</ref> The next day, Pepi made his competitive debut for FC Dallas against OKC Energy, starting in the 4–0 victory at [[Toyota Stadium (Texas)|Toyota Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web |title=FC Dallas 4–0 OKC Energy |url=https://us.soccerway.com/matches/2019/06/13/united-states/us-open-cup/football-club-dallas/okc-energy/3025076/ |website=Soccerway}}</ref> He appeared again for FC Dallas in the next round on June 19, starting in the 2–1 defeat.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Carrick |first1=Buzz |title=The Breakdown: US Open Cup - New Mexico United at FC Dallas |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/sports/fc-dallas/2019/06/21/the-breakdown-us-open-cup-new-mexico-united-at-fc-dallas/ |access-date=September 8, 2021 |work=Dallas Morning News |date=June 20, 2019}}</ref>

On June 21, 2019, Pepi was signed by [[FC Dallas]] to a [[Homegrown Player Rule (Major League Soccer)|homegrown player]] deal, becoming the club's fourth youngest academy signing at 16 years and 163 days old.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Butler |first1=Dylan |title=FC Dallas sign 16-year-old forward Ricardo Pepi to Homegrown contract |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/fc-dallas-sign-16-year-old-forward-ricardo-pepi-homegrown-contract |access-date=September 8, 2021 |work=Major League Soccer |date=June 21, 2019}}</ref> The next day, on June 22, Pepi made his [[Major League Soccer]] debut, coming on as an 84th-minute substitute in a 3–0 home victory over [[Toronto FC]].<ref>{{cite web |title=FC Dallas 3–0 Toronto FC |url=https://us.soccerway.com/matches/2019/06/23/united-states/mls/football-club-dallas/toronto-fc/2959996/ |website=Soccerway}}</ref> He finished his first season with FC Dallas with nine appearances and 0 goals.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bogert |first1=Tom |title=Cerrillo, Pepi lead five FC Dallas academy products to train with Bayern Munich |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/cerrillo-pepi-lead-five-fc-dallas-academy-products-train-bayern-munich |access-date=September 8, 2021 |work=Major League Soccer |date=November 4, 2019}}</ref>

On March 7, 2020, Pepi scored his first professional goal for FC Dallas, a 96th-minute equalizer in a 2–2 draw against the [[CF Montréal|Montreal Impact]].<ref>{{cite web |title=FC Dallas 2–2 Montreal Impact |url=https://us.soccerway.com/matches/2020/03/07/united-states/mls/football-club-dallas/montreal-impacts/3195765/ |website=Soccerway}}</ref> He scored his second goal of the season on September 9 in a 3–2 defeat away against [[Minnesota United FC|Minnesota United]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Minnesota United 3–2 FC Dallas |url=https://us.soccerway.com/matches/2020/09/10/united-states/mls/nsc-minnesota-stars/football-club-dallas/3333330/ |website=Soccerway}}</ref> On November 22, Pepi scored an equalizer for FC Dallas after trailing 1–0 in second-half stoppage time in the first round of the [[2020 MLS Cup Playoffs]] against the [[Portland Timbers]]. The match would eventually be decided in a penalty shootout, with Pepi converting his penalty in the lead up to FC Dallas advancing 8–7.<ref>{{cite web |title=Portland Timbers 1–1 FC Dallas |url=https://us.soccerway.com/matches/2020/11/23/united-states/mls/portland-timbers-mls/football-club-dallas/3420827/ |website=Soccerway}}</ref>

====2021 season====
[[File:Ricardo Pepi Football Americana 2021 01.png|thumb|left|200px|Pepi in 2021.]]

On April 17, Pepi made his first appearance of the [[2021 FC Dallas season|2021 season]] against the [[Colorado Rapids]], coming on as an 81st-minute substitute in the 0–0 draw.<ref>{{cite web |title=FC Dallas 0–0 Colorado Rapids |url=https://us.soccerway.com/matches/2021/04/18/united-states/mls/football-club-dallas/colorado-rapids/3471811/ |website=Soccerway}}</ref> In the next match on April 24, Pepi scored his first goal of the season, a consolation for FC Dallas in a 3–1 away defeat against the [[San Jose Earthquakes]].<ref>{{cite web |title=San Jose Earthquakes 3–1 FC Dallas |url=https://us.soccerway.com/matches/2021/04/24/united-states/mls/san-jose-earthquakes/football-club-dallas/3471819/ |website=Soccerway}}</ref> From that match on, Pepi would continue to feature as a regular starter for [[Luchi Gonzalez]] and on June 19, Pepi scored his second goal of the season against [[Minnesota United FC|Minnesota United]]. His goal was an equalizer in a 1–1 draw.<ref>{{cite web |title=FC Dallas 1–1 Minnesota United |url=https://us.soccerway.com/matches/2021/06/20/united-states/mls/football-club-dallas/nsc-minnesota-stars/3481277/ |website=Soccerway}}</ref> He then scored both goals for FC Dallas in a 2–1 victory against the [[New England Revolution]] on June 27.<ref>{{cite web |title=FC Dallas 2–1 New England Revolution |url=https://us.soccerway.com/matches/2021/06/28/united-states/mls/football-club-dallas/new-england-revolution/3481309/ |website=Soccerway}}</ref>

On July 24, Pepi scored his first professional hat-trick in a 4–0 home victory against the [[LA Galaxy]]. The three goals in a single match made him the youngest player in [[Major League Soccer]] history to score a hat-trick.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Panizo |first1=Franco |title=FC Dallas relishes Ricardo Pepi's historic hat-trick: "He is the kid of the present" |url=https://sbisoccer.com/2021/07/fc-dallas-relishes-ricardo-pepis-historic-hat-trick-he-is-the-kid-of-the-present |access-date=September 9, 2021 |work=SBI Soccer |date=July 25, 2021}}</ref> A week later, on August 4, it was announced that Pepi was selected by [[Bob Bradley]] to participate in the [[2021 MLS All-Star Game]] against the [[Liga MX|Liga MX All-Stars]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Morgan |first1=Andy |title=El Paso native Ricardo Pepi selected for 2021 MLS All-Star Game |url=https://www.ktsm.com/sports/local-sports/el-paso-native-ricardo-pepi-selected-for-2021-mls-all-star-game/ |access-date=September 9, 2021 |work=KTSM.com |date=August 4, 2021}}</ref> During the match on August 25, Pepi came on as a halftime substitute as the match ended 1–1 in regulation time, going into a penalty shootout.<ref>{{Cite web |last=mlssoccer |title=FC Dallas hail heroics of Ricardo Pepi after penalty kick triumph over Portland Timbers {{!}} MLSSoccer.com |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/fc-dallas-hail-heroics-ricardo-pepi-after-penalty-kick-triumph-over-portland-tim |access-date=2023-09-21 |website=mlssoccer |language=en}}</ref> During the shootout, Pepi scored the winning goal for the Major League Soccer All-Stars to give the league a 3–2 victory.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Reineking |first1=Jim |title=MLS All-Star team prevails over Liga MX All-Stars in penalty shootout as Ricardo Pepi makes winning kick |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/soccer/2021/08/25/mls-liga-mx-all-star-game-ricardo-pepi-decisive-kick/5597369001/ |access-date=September 9, 2021 |work=USA Today |date=August 26, 2021}}</ref>

In his next match, on August 29 against [[Austin FC]], Pepi scored two goals for FC Dallas in a 5–3 away victory.<ref>{{cite web |title=Austin FC 3–5 FC Dallas |url=https://us.soccerway.com/matches/2021/08/30/united-states/mls/austin/football-club-dallas/3481466/ |website=Soccerway}}</ref> He scored 13 goals in 31 appearances during the 2021 regular season and was named [[MLS Young Player of the Year Award|MLS Young Player of the Year]].<ref>{{cite news |date=December 18, 2021 |title=FC Dallas' Ricardo Pepi named 2021 US Soccer Young Male Player of the Year |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/fc-dallas-forward-ricardo-pepi-named-2021-us-soccer-young-player-of-the-year |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=November 27, 2024}}</ref>

=== FC Augsburg ===
On January 3, 2022, it was announced that Pepi had signed with [[FC Augsburg]] of the [[Bundesliga]]. The transfer fee was reported to be $20 million plus add-ons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/sources-fc-dallas-transferring-ricardo-pepi-to-augsburg-for-club-record-fee|title=FC Dallas transfer Ricardo Pepi to Bundesliga's Augsburg in club-record move &#124; MLSSoccer.com|website=mlssoccer}}</ref> The move made him the [[List of most expensive American soccer transfers|most expensive American MLS player]] to sign for a European club, the most expensive transfer by Augsburg, and the second most expensive player to transfer from MLS to a European league.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gonzalez |first1=Rogers |title=USMNT and FC Dallas striker Ricardo Pepi completes move to relegation-threatened Augsburg in Bundesliga |url=https://www.cbssports.com/soccer/news/usmnt-and-fc-dallas-striker-ricardo-pepi-completes-move-to-relegation-threatened-augsburg-in-bundesliga/ |website=[[CBS Sports]] |publisher=[[CBS]] |access-date=January 3, 2022 |date=January 3, 2022}}</ref> He made his league debut for Augsburg on January 8, coming on in the 60th minute in a 3–1 defeat to Hoffenheim.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sciaretta |first1=Brian |title=Pepi makes Augsburg debut while Adams. Richards, McKennie impresses |url=http://www.americansoccernow.com/articles/pepi-makes-augsburg-debut-while-adams-richards-mckennie-impresses |website=American Soccer Now |access-date=14 January 2022 |date=10 August 2022}}</ref>

==== Loan to FC Groningen ====
[[File:GAE - FC Groningen - 52877441697 (Ricardo Pepi).jpg|thumb|left|200px|Pepi with [[FC Groningen|Groningen]] in 2023.]]

On September 1, 2022, it was announced that Pepi would go on a year-long loan to [[Eredivisie]] outfit [[FC Groningen]] for the duration of the [[2022–23 FC Groningen season|2022–23 season]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Pepi: 'Ik ben hongerig naar doelpunten' |url=https://www.fcgroningen.nl/nieuws/pepi-ik-ben-hongerig-naar-doelpunten/2 |website=fcgroningen.nl |access-date=September 1, 2022 |language=Dutch |date=September 1, 2022}}</ref> In his competitive debut for the club against [[SC Cambuur|Cambuur]] he tallied an assist on the game's only goal.<ref>{{cite web|title=USMNT's Ricardo Pepi sets up winner in Groningen win over Cambuur|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/fc-groningen/story/4744154/usmnts-ricardo-pepi-sets-up-winner-in-groningen-win-over-cambuur|website=espn.com|access-date=October 5, 2022|date=September 11, 2022}}</ref> Pepi's hot start continued in the following match in which he broke an 11-month goal drought in a 2–1 defeat to [[Sparta Rotterdam]]. His most recent goal had come on October 7, 2021, in a 2–0 victory over [[Jamaica national football team|Jamaica]] for the [[United States national men's soccer team|United States]] in World Cup qualifying, marking him just 20 days shy of a year without scoring a competitive goal.<ref>{{cite web|title=USMNT striker Ricardo Pepi ends 30-game, 345-day drought with goal for Groningen|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/united-states-usa/story/4748883/usmnt-striker-ricardo-pepi-ends-30-game345-day-drought-with-goal-for-groningen|website=espn.com|access-date=October 5, 2022|date=September 17, 2022}}</ref>

Following the September international break, Pepi notched his second goal in as many league games, scoring Groningen's only goal as they suffered a 4–1 defeat to [[AZ Alkmaar]].<ref>{{cite web|title=USMNT striker Ricardo Pepi scores in 2nd straight match for Groningen|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/united-states-usa/story/4758936/usmnt-striker-ricardo-pepi-scores-in-2nd-straight-match-for-groningen|website=espn.com|access-date=October 5, 2022|date=October 1, 2022}}</ref> The following week he scored a brace in a 3–2 defeat to [[RKC Waalwijk]], in the process becoming the first [[Eredivisie]] player in the 21st century to score or assist on five goals in his first four league games.<ref>{{cite web|title=USMNT striker Ricardo Pepi scores 2 goals for Groningen to continue hot streak|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/united-states-usa/story/4763818/usmnt-striker-ricardo-pepi-scores-2-goals-for-groningen-to-continue-hot-streak|website=espn.com|access-date=October 16, 2022|date=October 7, 2022|quote=He is also the first player this century to be directly involved in five goals in his first four Eredivisie matches, according to Opta, having also registered one assist.}}</ref> In a 3–0 victory over [[Excelsior Rotterdam|Excelsior]] on February 25, Pepi scored his tenth goal of his loan spell in just his 20th competitive game for Groningen.<ref>{{cite web|title=USMNT's Ricardo Pepi nets 10th goal of the season as striker continues to find confidence at Groningen|url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/usmnt-pepi-groningen-double-digit/blt925b52c6eccf30ae|work=Goal|first=Ryan|last=Tolmich|access-date=February 25, 2023|date=February 25, 2023}}</ref>

Despite playing for a relegation-threatened side, Pepi earned a spot on the official Eredivisie Team of the Month for February 2023 as the only outfield player not from league powerhouses [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]], [[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]], and [[Feyenoord]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Pepi makes Eredivisie team of the month for still-struggling Groningen|url=https://prosoccerwire.usatoday.com/2023/03/03/pepi-eredivisie-team-of-the-month-groningen-usmnt/|work=Pro Soccer Wire|first=Jason|last=Anderson|access-date=March 12, 2023|date=March 3, 2023}}</ref>

===PSV Eindhoven===
On July 7, 2023, Pepi signed a five-year contract with PSV Eindhoven after the Dutch club agreed to pay $9.8 million to Augsburg for Pepi's transfer.<ref name=":1" /> On November 29, 2023, he scored his first [[UEFA Champions League]] goal, a 3–2 game winner in stoppage time against [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]], which qualified his club to the [[2023–24 UEFA Champions League knockout phase|knockout phase]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Media |first=P. A. |date=2023-11-29 |title=Champions League: Pepi winner caps PSV's wild comeback at Sevilla |language=en-GB |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/nov/29/champions-league-sevilla-psv-bayern-benfica-inter |access-date=2023-11-29 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

==International career==
Born in the United States, Pepi was eligible to play for both the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] and [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] through his parents.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Boehm |first1=Charles |title=Ricardo Pepi on US-Mexico international choice: "I'm just stuck in the middle" |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/ricardo-pepi-on-us-mexico-international-choice-i-m-just-stuck-in-the-middle |access-date=September 9, 2021 |work=Major League Soccer |date=August 24, 2021}}</ref> He had also previously attended training camps for both the [[United States men's national under-17 soccer team|United States under-17]] and [[Mexico national under-17 football team|Mexico under-17]] sides.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bloomquist |first1=Bret |title=Ricardo Pepi of El Paso appears poised to break into Major League Soccer for FC Dallas |url=https://www.elpasotimes.com/story/sports/soccer/2019/04/16/ricardo-pepi-el-paso-appears-poised-break-into-mls-fc-dallas/3440748002/ |work=El Paso Times |date=April 16, 2019}}</ref> On April 22, 2019, Pepi was included in the United States under-17 squad by [[Raphaël Wicky]] for the [[2019 CONCACAF U-17 Championship|CONCACAF U-17 Championship]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Carrick |first1=Buzz |title=Ricardo Pepi named to US U17s for Concacaf U17 Championship |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/sports/fc-dallas/2019/04/22/ricardo-pepi-named-to-us-u17s-for-concacaf-u17-championship/ |access-date=September 9, 2021 |work=Dallas Morning News |date=April 22, 2019}}</ref> On May 12, Pepi scored his first international goal against [[Panama national under-17 football team|Panama]], followed by a brace against [[Canada men's national under-17 soccer team|Canada]] to help the United States advance to the final.<ref>{{cite web |title=United States U17 3–0 Panama U17 |url=https://us.soccerway.com/matches/2019/05/12/nc-america/concacaf-u17/united-states-under-17/panama-u17/2987415/ |website=Soccerway}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=United States U17 4–0 Canada U17 |url=https://us.soccerway.com/matches/2019/05/14/nc-america/concacaf-u17/united-states-under-17/canada-u17/2987418/ |website=Soccerway}}</ref> In October 2019, Pepi was included again in the under-17 squad, this time for the [[2019 FIFA U-17 World Cup|FIFA U-17 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Henry Jr. |first1=Larry |title=Reyna, Busio headline USMNT Under-17 World Cup roster |url=https://sbisoccer.com/2019/10/reyna-busio-headline-usmnt-u-17-world-cup-roster |access-date=September 9, 2021 |work=SBI Soccer |date=October 10, 2019}}</ref>

On August 26, 2021, manager [[Gregg Berhalter]] selected Pepi in the United States squad for [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification – CONCACAF third round|2022 FIFA World Cup qualification]].<ref>{{cite news |title=FC Dallas striker Ricardo Pepi earns USMNT call up for FIFA World Cup Qualifiers |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/sports/fc-dallas/2021/08/26/fc-dallas-striker-ricardo-pepi-earns-usmnt-call-up-for-fifa-world-cup-qualifiers/ |access-date=September 9, 2021 |work=Dallas Morning News |date=August 26, 2021}}</ref> On September 8, 2021, Pepi made his debut for the United States and scored the winning goal in a 4–1 away victory against [[Honduras national football team|Honduras]]. His goal was the second of the match, giving the United States a 2–1 lead.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Ricardo Pepi Sparks USMNT's World Cup Qualifying Comeback Win vs. Honduras |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2021/09/09/usmnt-honduras-world-cup-qualifying-video-updates-highlights-pulisic |access-date=September 9, 2021 |magazine=Sports Illustrated |date=September 9, 2021}}</ref> He scored twice in his second match, a 2–0 qualifying win against [[Jamaica national football team|Jamaica]] played in [[Austin, Texas]].<ref>{{cite news |date=October 7, 2021 |title=USMNT's Ricardo Pepi scores 2 goals in World Cup qualifier win over Jamaica |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4198219/2021/10/08/usmnts-ricardo-pepi-scores-2-goals-in-world-cup-qualifier-win-over-jamaica/ |work=[[The Athletic]] |access-date=October 7, 2021}}</ref>

Despite the early success, Pepi was ultimately not called up to the team's 26-man 2022 World Cup roster.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bernstein |first1=Dan |title=Explained: Why Ricardo Pepi was snubbed from USMNT's World Cup squad |url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/explained-why-ricardo-pepi-was-snubbed-from-usmnt-world-cup-squad/blt551ce77bae519661 |website=[[Goal (website)|Goal]] |access-date=December 6, 2022 |date=November 9, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Booth |first1=Chuck |title=FIFA World Cup 2022: USMNT Striker Ricardo Pepi responds after Gregg Berhalter snubs him for USA squad |url=https://www.cbssports.com/soccer/news/fifa-world-cup-2022-usmnt-striker-ricardo-pepi-responds-after-gregg-berhalter-snubs-him-for-usa-squad/ |website=[[CBS Sports]] |access-date=December 6, 2022 |date=November 14, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Quillen |first1=Ian Nicholas |title=USMNT Snubs Ricardo Pepi, Zack Steffen Show Leaving MLS For Europe Can Backfire |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ianquillen/2022/11/09/usmnt-snubs-ricardo-pepi-zack-steffen-show-leaving-mls-for-europe-can-backfire/?sh=33a4c6dc42bf |website=[[Forbes]] |access-date=December 6, 2022 |date=November 9, 2022}}</ref> In his first international match following the World Cup, Pepi scored his fourth and fifth international goals as part of a brace in a 7–1 [[2022–23 CONCACAF Nations League A|Nations League]] victory over [[Grenada national football team|Grenada]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Tolmich|first=Ryan|title=Ricardo Pepi and Christian Pulisic steal the show! Winners and Losers after the USMNT fire SEVEN past Grenada|url=https://www.goal.com/en-in/lists/pepi-pulisic-usmnt-grenada-winners-losers/blt97730a9f3dc7e55a#cs5a22b59c07b33964|website=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|access-date=March 25, 2023|date=March 24, 2023}}</ref> Four days later, he scored the game-winning goal against [[El Salvador national football team|El Salvador]] to send the United States into the 2023 Nations League semifinals.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Butler |first1=Dylan |title=Ricardo Pepi powers USMNT past El Salvador, into Nations League semifinals |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/ricardo-pepi-powers-usmnt-past-el-salvador-into-nations-league-semifinals |website=MLSSoccer.com |access-date=March 27, 2023 |date=March 27, 2023}}</ref> In the Nations League semifinal against [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]], Pepi scored off the bench securing the 3–0 U.S. win.

On October 2, 2024, Pepi was included in [[Mauricio Pochettino]]'s first roster as the head coach of the USMNT for friendlies against [[Panama national football team|Panama]] and [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=New USMNT Head Coach Mauricio Pochettino Names 25-Player Roster for First Training Camp And Matches Against Panama and Mexico |url=https://www.ussoccer.com/stories/2024/10/mauricio-pochettino-names-us-mens-national-team-roster-for-october-matches-panama-mexico |access-date=2024-11-14 |website=www.ussoccer.com |language=en}}</ref> In the October 12 match against Panama, Pepi scored off the bench to ensure a 2–0 U.S. win.<ref>{{Cite web |title=USMNT Earns 2-0 Shutout Win Against Panama in Head Coach Mauricio Pochettino's Debut |url=https://www.ussoccer.com/stories/2024/10/usa-vs-panama-score-result-goals-stats-match-recap |access-date=2024-11-14 |website=www.ussoccer.com |language=en}}</ref> On October 13, Pepi returned to [[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]] due to a minor injury, and was not present for the second match of the international window.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Five Players Depart USMNT Camp As Team Heads To Guadalajara For Rare Friendly In Mexico |url=https://www.ussoccer.com/stories/2024/10/five-players-depart-usmnt-camp |access-date=2024-11-14 |website=www.ussoccer.com |language=en}}</ref>

